1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. TDD (code tasks): Write tests FIRST that verify done_when criteria, then implement until tests pass
3. Tests are MANDATORY for code tasks — Code Reviewer will reject code without tests. Invoke skill: testing.
   Tests must be discoverable via standard runners (e.g. pytest, go test) — not just runnable when explicitly named.
4. Dependency bootstrap exception: if validation/build/test commands fail because declared project dependencies are not installed in this worktree, you may run only an existing project-scoped bootstrap command to restore them. First query `liza get config.post_worktree_cmd --json`; if configured, run that command from {{.Worktree}}. If absent, use only the repo's existing lockfile-preserving install workflow. This is pre-authorized for validation only: do not edit dependency manifests or lockfiles, install global/system tooling, or add/upgrade/remove dependencies unless the task scope explicitly requires it. If bootstrap needs those changes, mark BLOCKED with the failing command and stderr.
5. Exempt: doc-only, config-only, or spec-only tasks (no code = no tests required)
6. TDD waiver: For cosmetic-only changes (comment fixes, formatting), set tdd_not_required in checkpoint with justification
7. Mechanical test updates: For structural refactoring (file split/move), updating test
   file-path references or imports to reflect the new file layout is in-scope and does
   not trigger the TDD requirement in item 3. The test's invariant (what it validates)
   must be preserved.
8. Invoke skill: clean-code at the end of the implementation
9. Validate ALL done_when criteria are met
10. If context exhaustion is near (~90%): run liza handoff --json with summary + next_action (or structured fields), then exit with code 42
