   a. The required story files exist under {{.Worktree}}/specs/stories/{{.GoalSlug}}/{{.EpicSlug}}/ and match the assigned capability scope.
   b. Git readiness: stage the intended files, create the submission commit, verify `git -C {{.Worktree}} status --short` is clean, then capture the submission SHA with `git -C {{.Worktree}} rev-parse HEAD`.
   c. Submission proof: `liza submit-for-review` must actually run successfully after step 7b; do not stop at "ready for review".
8. Submit using liza submit-for-review --json only after all checks in step 7 pass, using the SHA from step 7b.
{{- else if eq .Role "architect"}}

IMPLEMENTATION PHASE:
1. Work ONLY in the worktree directory. Use git -C {{.Worktree}} for all git commands.
2. Read the goal spec ({{.SpecRef}}) thoroughly to understand what must be built.
{{- if gt (len .ParentTaskContexts) 0}}
3. Review the parent task context above — these are the upstream deliverables you are consolidating.
   Read any referenced spec or plan documents to understand the full scope.
{{- end}}
4. Explore the codebase to understand the existing architecture and relevant components.
5. Architecture document:
   Run: mkdir -p {{.Worktree}}/specs/arch-plan/{{.GoalSlug}}
   Capture a timestamp by running: date -u +'%Y%m%d-%H%M%S'
   Save your architecture document to: {{.Worktree}}/specs/arch-plan/{{.GoalSlug}}/TIMESTAMP-{{.TaskID}}.md
   All later references to "the arch doc" mean the exact path chosen here.
   The document should define:
   - Component boundaries and responsibilities
   - Interface contracts between components
   - Data flow and structural decisions
   - Cross-cutting concerns and how they are addressed
   - Decomposition into code-planning scopes (each becomes a downstream task)
6. For EACH code-planning scope in your architecture, call liza set-task-output --json with structured entries.
   Each entry becomes a code-planning child task after merge. The Architecture Reviewer will verify these.
   Fields: desc (scope boundary), done_when (falsifiable), scope (what the code-planner covers),
   spec_ref (goal spec — same for all entries), arch_ref (repo-relative path to the arch doc from step 5),
   depends_on (optional array of sibling index strings for ordering constraints).
   Extract each field verbatim from the arch doc — do not compose from memory or paraphrase.
7. Update worktree artifacts required by DONE WHEN.
8. Validate done_when criteria with concrete checks.
9. PRE-SUBMIT SELF-CHECK (MANDATORY — do NOT call liza submit-for-review --json until all pass):
   a. Each output[] entry has a single, well-scoped code-planning intent.
   b. Each output[] done_when is falsifiable: a specific observable outcome, not vague.
   c. Verify the arch doc contains a decomposition section mapping to each output[] entry.
   d. All output[] entries have arch_ref set to the arch doc path.
   e. Spec compliance: the decomposition covers the full scope of the goal spec.
   f. Shared-file audit: if two output[] entries may touch the same files, add depends_on.
   g. Git readiness: stage the intended files, create the submission commit, verify `git -C {{.Worktree}} status --short` is clean, then capture the submission SHA with `git -C {{.Worktree}} rev-parse HEAD`.
   h. Submission proof: `liza submit-for-review` must actually run successfully after step 9g; do not treat the arch doc plus `liza set-task-output` as sufficient.
10. Submit using liza submit-for-review --json only after all checks in step 9 pass, using the SHA from step 9g.
{{- end}}
